# zen-term: workspaces reference
#
# Copy to ~/.config/zen-term/workspaces (or $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/zen-term/workspaces) and
# add a section per workspace. This list is deliberate and hand-curated. zen-term does
# NOT scan any directory. Each section becomes an entry in the ⌘⇧P picker.
#
# Format: INI-style. A `[Title]` line opens a section; `key = value` lines below it
# configure that workspace until the next header. Lines starting with `#` and blank
# lines are ignored; unknown keys are ignored. A section with no `path` is skipped, a
# malformed `env` line is dropped, and nothing here can crash the app (bad lines are
# logged and skipped). Manage workspaces from inside the app too, in Settings → Workspaces
# (add / edit / delete), or the ＋ row in the ⌘⇧P picker to add-and-open one. Hand-edits
# to this file are picked up the next time you open the ⌘⇧P picker (or on restart).
#
# The section header is the title: it's shown in the picker and pinned as the tab name,
# so it's independent of the folder name (`[ZenTerm]` can point at ~/Dev/zen-term).
#
# Opening a workspace applies its "recipe": the first pane runs `main`, the drawers named
# by `right`/`bottom` open running their commands, focus lands on `focus`, and `env` is
# injected into every pane and drawer. A section with only a `path` is the minimal
# default: one shell pane, both drawers collapsed, cwd = the workspace dir.
#
# Fields:
#   [Title]  (required)  section header → picker label + pinned tab name
#   path     (required)  working directory (`~` is expanded)
#   main     (optional)  first-pane program; absent or `shell` → a plain shell
#   right    (optional)  right-drawer command; absent → closed; `shell` → a plain shell
#   bottom   (optional)  bottom-drawer command; absent → closed; `shell` → a plain shell
#   focus    (optional)  main | right | bottom                       (default main)
#   env      (optional)  KEY=VALUE, repeatable; injected into every surface
#
# A value with spaces may be quoted: bottom = "npm run dev".
#
# Example: an editor + AI + dev-server workspace (uncomment and edit, or write your own):
#
# [ZenTerm]
# path   = ~/Dev/zen-term
# main   = nvim
# right  = claude
# bottom = shell
# focus  = main
# env    = NODE_ENV=development
# env    = PORT=3000
